Dec 3 2007 	Comfortable Luxury	I had been following the reviews of the Lowell for quite a while now and had some trepidation about staying there before our November stay. This review is for the people who read the same reviews and feel some sort of doubt if they should book there or not -- trust me, you can put your fears to rest !!!The hotel is historic, and located about 2 blocks from Central Park on a fairly quiet street on the Upper East Side. Historic means that the elevators are slow and small, which can be frustrating sometimes. But, a small thing when you look at the overall service the hotel provides. The F subway line is about 2 blocks away, plus the 6 subway line was about 4 blocks away. We found we mostly used these two lines to get around NYC. The staff were not snobbish at all and were all very friendly, down to earth, and welcoming. Kudos to Antonio, the evening concierge, especially. He would always greet us in a warm, friendly manner and was always interested in a short chat on how our day went or in a debate the virtues of a particular restaurant.We stayed in a King Jr. Suite. The suite was spacious, beautifully decorated, and is very true to the pics on their website. Everything was extremely clean and in good repair, no worn furniture or dirty walls or peeling wallpaper as reported in another review. The bed was just a tad firm, but I'm splitting hairs here, and is made up with very high end linens. The bathroom was extremely spacious, all beautifully done in marble and comes with yummy Bulgari Green Tea amenities. Get to know your maid and be on friendly terms, and she'll leave you more to take home ;o)We ordered room service twice from the Post House, and each time our food came well-prepared and hot, within 1/2 an hour, even during busy times. Portions are extremely large, so you may want to split entrees if you are not positively starving. Our faves were the coconut cake; lots of white cake layers sandwiched between coconut mousse and the Lobster Club sandwich.The service at the Lowell is top notch, we have stayed at Four Seasons Hotels and I would say it is comparable. For example, there are plenty of umbrellas on rainy days, and when you come back from a wet outing, they automatically exchange your wet umbrella for a dry one. We had mentioned it was my birthday and one evening a very large chocolate mousse cake was delivered to our room, gratis, with a candle. After the first day, the staff greet you by name. Little things like the above make all the difference and should be expected as well, as it is not cheap to stay at the Lowell. There is also a gym that is fairly well equipped, with plenty of bottled water, fresh fruit and every type of energy bar/ protein bar you can think of that you can help yourself to. Also, there is also a free computer and printer to use, which saves you from bringing a laptop.All in all, we feel it is worth it to stay at the Lowell, and will save our pennies to do so again. We felt totally pampered and relaxed, plus the friendly staff made it a pleasure to come back &quot;home&quot;. I can truly say we had a wonderful experience at the Lowell and look forward to staying there again soon.	
