Dec 16 2004	Don't look for Nick and Jessica here	The Lowell caters to those who do not wish to stay at an &quot;in&quot; hotel, though, I think it's standard is better than most well-know grand hotels in the city. It's not affiliated with any chain, and you can tell the moment you arrive. There are no key cards; instead actual room keys that you leave with the desk staff (whom after the first time you reurn, have their arm extended with your key before you open your mouth). Since this was an old apartment building, each room has a full kitchen (the deluxe rooms have kitchenettes with Sub-Zero brand appliances) and rooms are exactly what you except a hotel of this caliber to be (Bulgari porducts, TVs in the tub, etc). Service and attention to detail have the corporate hotels beat hands-down. Four Seasons and St. Regis (stayed at SR, both have double the rate) can't compete. Ice comes in two minutes, and room service is quick. The low turnover in staff is amazing. I live in the city and when my parents visit, once or twice a year, the staff always remembers me and sends me up without calling them. One complaint, there is not a bar with a sitting area (neighboring Post House has a door to its restaurant and offers full room service in addition to the hotels own kitchen, but has a stand-only bar). However, guests have signing privileges at Club Macanudo next door (and Le Bilbouquet bistrot across the street). All in all, this is not the place to see an be seen and the staff and guests wouldn't have it any other way. And who has actual terraces and in-suite fireplaces that work? (they will actually come and build a fire...for a fee, of course. This is the East Side after all). NB: Leading Hotels (and even Orbitz) can have rates at $310, even during the holidays. If you want to go back and brag that you stayed at a Peninsula or Mandarin, do it, but you'll pay more and get less.	
Sep 21 2004	European Luxury in the USA	Having stayed at the The Lowell 8 times in the last 3 years, it is my favorite Hotel in all of New York, and possibly the USA. If you want to get the feel of being a New Yorker living near Central Park &amp; within steps of the best shopping in the city, you won't want to miss coming &quot;home&quot; to The Lowell. I was there for Christmas in 2003 with my pekingese, and we had the best Christmas I've ever had. Room service is superb, the concierge will arrange whatever requests you may have, and the desk staff treated me &amp; my dog like we were 1st class. The rooms are very quiet and furnishings are very comfortable. Enjoy your trip to New York &amp; please consider this your fine luxurious peaceful home away from home.	
Aug 5 2004 	Understated Elegance....	When the Ritz and Plaza Athene were booked I decided to try The Lowell last May (2004). It was a very good value and just steps from the best shopping on Madison Avenue, I went with low expectations so had little to lose. On first impression the lobby seemed dark &amp; a bit dreary, but the welcoming staff &amp; unasked for room upgrade quickly made up for it. As a woman traveling alone, I prefer small boutique hotels with a european feeling and my idea of heaven is a bed filled with down pillows, a bubble bath and great room service when I'm away from home... and The Lowell had it all. Right down to the Bulgari toiletries and Frederic Fakai shampoo! My room was spacious, tastefully furnished, and I couldn't wait to get back for 'High Tea' at the end of the day (clotted cream &amp; all). If five star service is a priority, you may be disappointed, but if quiet, privacy, and understated elegance makes you happy you will be delighted with The Lowell.	
Dec 22 2003	very unhappy with service	I absolutely LOVED our room. We stayed 5 nights and it truly felt like we had our own apartment in the city. However, the service was terrible! We booked a $750 suite and were upgraded by the hotel manager to an even nicer room ($1,200) without having to ask. The front desk staff was rude each and every time I spoke to them. They didn't recognize me as a guest once during my 5 day stay. They neglected to bring packages to my room. They lost my husbands lap top for a few hours. A houskeeper and repairmen working on another room on our floor raided our kitchen of alcohol and candy bars and the front desk refused to take them off the bill. Also houskeeping neglected to place a sign on our fireplace informing us of the $20 per day fee for it's use. We used it every day and were shocked upon checkout to have $100 in charges. Again, the desk refused to remove the charge. I even suggested that they accompany me upstairs to prove the sign wasn't there. The staff member then accused me of &quot;disposing of the sign&quot;. I received a refund for the extra charges after writing a letter to the hotel manager. He was very nice about it and has offered us a free night next time we are in NYC. I'm a little scared to give them another try though, especially with so many fabulous hotels in the city.	
Jul 5 2003	Superb and understated	I have stayed at The Lowell several times and it is simply superb in every respect. The staff is the best anywhere and service is impeccable. I give it an unqualified &quot;Five Stars&quot;.	
